did.abstract: This collection comprises the papers of noted philosoper and Yale professor, Ruth Barcan Marcus. The papers primarily document Marcus' scholarly contributions to the field of philosophy, as well as her teaching career at Yale and other universities. The collection includes correspondence, subject files, notebooks, writings, teaching materials, audio recordings, and electronic files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection comprises the papers of noted philosoper and Yale professor, Ruth Barcan Marcus. The papers primarily document Marcus' scholarly contributions to the field of philosophy, as well as her teaching career at Yale and other universities. The collection includes correspondence, subject files, notebooks, writings, teaching materials, audio recordings, and electronic files.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Ruth Barcan Marcus was a philosopher and a professor in the Yale University Philosophy Department, noted for her advances in the field of logic, as well as her outspoken advocacy for women in philosophy. Dr. Marcus was born Ruth Charlotte Barcan on August 2, 1921, and was raised in the Bronx, NY. She earned a bachelor's degree in mathematics and philosophy from New York University, as well as a master's degree and a doctorate in philosophy from Yale.

Dr. Marcus taught at Roosevelt University, the University of Illinois at Chicago, and at Northwestern University before joining the Yale faculty in 1973. She is noted for her advances in the quantification of modal logic and the theory of direct reference. She also wrote significant works on identity, essentialism, possibilia, belief, and moral conflict. She is perhaps most well-known for the development of the Barcan formula, an essential thesis of modal logic.
After retiring from Yale in 1992, Dr. Marcus taught at the University of California, Irvine. She died at her home in New Haven on February 19, 2012.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Materials in Series V are open for research. Per our agreement with the donor materials in Series I, II, IV, VI, and VII are restricted until January 1, 2028; and materials in Series III are restricted until January 1, 2031.

Original audiovisual materials, as well as preservation and duplicating masters, may not be played. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist must pay for a use copy, which is retained by the repository. Researchers wishing to obtain an additional copy for their personal use should consult Copying Services information on the Manuscripts and Archives web site.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The papers are arranged into seven series: I. Correspondence, 1937-2011. II. Subject files, 1940-2011. III. Departmental files, 1973-2008. IV. Notebooks, 1947-1978. V. Teaching and course files, 1959-1995. VI. Writings, Speeches, and Lectures, 1942-2010. VII. Electronic files, circa 1980-2011.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of a substantial body of both incoming and outgoing correspondence, primarily between Ruth Barcan Marcus and colleagues at Yale University, as well as in the broader philosophy field. The correspondence primarily concerns Marcus' scholarship, writings, and professional service, issues and goings-on within philosophy and academia, as well as solicitations of feedback from colleagues about their own work. In particular, her correspondence both up-and-coming and established female colleagues reflects her championing of the work of women philosophers, as well as the mentorship she provided to those of a younger generation.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of an assortment of files related to Ruth Barcan Marcus' research interests, scholarship, and professional service. A substantial number of the files concern the work of Marcus' colleagues in philosophy and other academic fields whose research and scholarship interested her. The series also includes a substantial body of biographical materials that Marcus compiled herself. These materials primarily document her professional accomplishments and employment history spanning the entirety of her career.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of files related to the Yale Philosophy Department during Ruth Barcan Marcus' tenure as a professor. The materials in the series consist of reports, meeting minutes, memoranda and notes pertaining to a variety of topics, including the recruitment, hiring and promotion of faculty, course curriculum, and administrative matters.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of notebooks kept by Ruth Barcan Marcus over a 30-year span from the late 1940s through the late 1970s. The content of the notebooks is a curious mix of notes on Marcus' research, writings, and classroom instruction, as well as drafts of correspondence, schedules and to-do lists, and personal notes. Many of the notebooks contain extensive mathematical formulas and problems, most likely related to her work in the field of modal logic.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of notes, outlines, syllabi, schedules, and other materials related to Ruth Barcan Marcus' teaching career. The bulk of these materials were produced during Marcus' tenure as a professor at Yale, though the dates of some files correspond to her academic appointments at the University of Illinois at Chicago and Northwestern University, respectively. Many of the materials are identified by the specific course taught, while others are identified by topic with no indication of the course for which documents were used.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series comprises scholarly papers, articles, and audtio recordings of speeches and lectures by Ruth Barcan Marcus, as well as notes, outlines, and correspondence related to her writings. The bulk of materials concerns the topics of modal logic and belief, two of Marcus' foremost research interests. The paper, "Women in Philosophy," delivered at an unspecified conference or event, details both Marcus' own experience as a woman in the field of philosophy, as well as her perspective on the status and role of women in philosophy throughout her life and career.
